[07:55] <brrt> lizmat: have you tried the jit-stack-walker on OS X
[07:55] <lizmat> brrt: no, I haven't
[07:55] <brrt> could you please :-)
[07:56] <brrt> I'm thinking of making it a compile time option
[07:56] <lizmat> ok, then I don't understand what it does
[07:57] <brrt> it is a branch :-)
[07:57] <brrt> what it does is:
[07:58] <brrt> currently every basic block in the JIT *has* to store the current position in the current thread frame
[08:03] <brrt> because otherwise the (relatively rare) exception mechanism and dynamic lexical mechanism don't know which inline / frame handler we are in, and fail
[08:04] <brrt> i.e. we *eagerly* load the current position
[08:04] <brrt> the idea of the jit-stack-walker branch is to make that less eager
[08:05] <lizmat> ok, so if there are no exceptions to handle, that's a win
[08:05] <brrt> correct
[08:05] <lizmat> does "return" count as an exception ?
[08:05] <brrt> on rakudo, yes
[08:06] <brrt> well, in some cases
[08:06] <lizmat> ok, so this would penalize everybody who uses explicit "return" in their code
[08:06] <lizmat> when not necessary
[08:06] <brrt> not necessarily
[08:06] <brrt> i mean, stack walking is a pretty cheap operation
[08:06] <brrt> given that the first few pages of the stack are already on cache
[08:07] <brrt> and every basic block entry is quite a bit more frequent than frame return
[08:07] <lizmat> ok, was just checking
[08:07] <lizmat> brb
[08:08] <brrt> (what it does is inspect the stack for the return address in the compiled JIT code, so we *know* the current position exactly)
